\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), \(D\) is a point on \(BC\), and \(AD\) bisects \(\angle BAC\). The area of \(\triangle ABD\) is twice the area of \(\triangle ADC\). If \(AD = b\) and \(DC = a\),}
\textbf{Using only the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines,}
\textbf{Prove that \(AC = \sqrt{a^2 + \frac{b^2}{2}}\).}

\textbf{Given a triangle \(ABC\) with centroid \(O\). Let \(P\) be a point in the same plane as \(ABC\) such that}
\[
\overrightarrow{OP} = \frac{\overrightarrow{OB} + \overrightarrow{OC}}{2} + \lambda \left( \frac{\overrightarrow{AB}}{|\overrightarrow{AB}| \cos B} + \frac{\overrightarrow{AC}}{|\overrightarrow{AC}| \cos C} \right).
\]
\textbf{Prove that as \(\lambda\) varies, the locus of point \(P\) passes through the circumcenter of \(\triangle ABC\).}

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\), the length of side \(BC\) is a fixed value \(a\), and}
\[
\frac{1 + \cos A}{\sin A} = \frac{1 + \cos B}{\sin B} + 1.
\]
\textbf{Prove that the perimeter of \(\triangle ABC\) is \(\leq (2 + \sqrt{5})a\).}

\textbf{Let \( x \in \mathbb{R} \), and denote by \([x]\) the greatest integer less than or equal to \( x \). The function \( y = [x] \) is called the floor function. This function has the following properties:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The domain of \( y = [x] \) is \(\mathbb{R}\), and its range is \(\mathbb{Z}\).
    \item Any real number can be expressed as the sum of its integer part and its fractional part, i.e., \( x = [x] + \{x\} \) where \( 0 \leq \{x\} < 1 \). Here, \([x]\) is the integer part of \( x \), and \(\{x\} = x - [x]\) is the fractional part of \( x \).
    \item \([n + x] = n + [x]\) for any integer \( n \in \mathbb{Z} \).
    \item If integers \( a \) and \( b \) satisfy \( a = bq + r \) where \( b > 0 \), \( q, r \in \mathbb{Z} \), and \( 0 \leq r < b \), then \(\left\lfloor \frac{a}{b} \right\rfloor = q\).
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Prove that for any positive integer \( n \geq 3 \),}
\[
\left\{ \frac{n(n+1)}{4n-2} \right\} > \left\{ \frac{n+1}{4} \right\}.
\]

\textbf{Prove that:}
\[
\sin^2 x \cdot \cos y + \sin^2 y \cdot \cos z + \sin^2 z \cdot \cos x < \frac{3}{2}
\]

\textbf{In \(\triangle ABC\),}
\[
9 \sin^2 A + 5 \sin^2 B - 3 \sin^2 C = 2 \sqrt{3} \sin A \sin B \sin C.
\]
\textbf{Prove that \(C\) is a constant value.}

\textbf{Given \(2n\) balls numbered \(1, 2, \ldots, 2n\) (\(n \in \mathbb{N}^*, n \geq 2\)), they are randomly divided into two groups, Group A and Group B, each containing \(n\) balls. Let the smallest and largest numbers in Group A be \(a_1\) and \(a_2\), respectively, and the smallest and largest numbers in Group B be \(b_1\) and \(b_2\), respectively. Define \(\xi = a_2 - a_1\) and \(\eta = b_2 - b_1\).}

\textbf{Let \(A\) be the event that the values of \(\xi\) and \(\eta\) are exactly equal. Prove that}
\[
\frac{1}{6} < P(A) \leq \frac{2}{3}.
\]

\textbf{Given a sequence \(\{a_n\}\). Two properties are provided:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item For any two terms \(a_i, a_j\) (\(i \geq j\)) in \(\{a_n\}\), there exists a term \(a_k\) in \(\{a_n\}\) such that \(a_k = a_i a_j\).
    \item For any three consecutive terms \(a_n, a_{n+1}, a_{n+2}\) in \(\{a_n\}\), it holds that \((a_n - a_{n+1} - a_{n+2})(a_n - \frac{1}{2}a_{n+1} - a_{n+2}) = 0\).
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{If the sequence \(\{a_n\}\) satisfies both properties and \(a_1 > 0\), \(a_2 < -1\), \(a_3 = 2\), prove that \(\{a_n\}\) is unique.}

\textbf{Let \(A\) be a finite set containing \(n\) elements. If \(m\) subsets \(A_1, A_2, \cdots, A_m\) of \(A\) satisfy the following conditions:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \(A_1, A_2, \cdots, A_m\) are all non-empty.
    \item The intersection of any two subsets among \(A_1, A_2, \cdots, A_m\) is an empty set.
    \item \(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \cdots \cup A_m = A\).
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Then \(A_1, A_2, \cdots, A_m\) is called an \(m\)-th order partition of set \(A\).}

\textbf{Let \(A_1, A_2, A_3\) be a 3rd-order partition of the set of positive integers \(A = \{a_1, a_2, \cdots, a_n\}\) (\(n \in \mathbb{N}^*\), \(n \geq 3\)). If \(A_1, A_2, A_3\) satisfy that for any element \(a_i\) in set \(A\), \(A_i = \{a_i\}\) where \(i \in \{1, 2, 3, \cdots, n\}\), and the sums of elements in \(A_2\) and \(A_3\) are equal, prove that \(n\) is an odd number.}

Denote \(|M|\) as the number of elements of the finite set \(M\). Given that \(m\) and \(n\) are positive integers, and the set \(S = \{1,2,\cdots,n\}\). If the sequence of sets \(Q: A_{1},A_{2},\cdots,A_{m}\) satisfies the following three properties, then \(Q\) is called a "balanced sequence":
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(|A_{k}|\geq2\), where \(k = 1,2,\cdots,m\);
    \item \(A_{k}\subsetneqq S\), where \(k = 1,2,\cdots,m\);
    \item For any two distinct elements \(i\) and \(j\) in \(S\), there exists a unique \(k\in\{1,2,\cdots,m\}\) such that \(\{i,j\}\subseteq A_{k}\).
\end{itemize}

Given that \(n\geq3\) and the sequence of sets \(Q: A_{1},A_{2},\cdots,A_{m}\) is a "balanced sequence".

Prove that \(m\geq n\).
